out of sight out of mind right? well that is exactly the reason my posts will be starting to get a little more hard to see. because i believe the hard, sad, disgusting things need to be seen in order to have real hope for a real change in this cruel world. iâ€™ve had a hand full of people just in the past week message me and tell me they are thinking about going vegan and that my posts break their hearts... as they should! there is nothing wrong with you because these type of posts break your heart! it means you have compassion within you! it means you deep down know what is right and what is wrong! my posts may suck! but imagine how bad the lives of these poor innocent souls suck! if this is hard for you to see, look harder and longer, look into their eyes and think about the horrors they see and go through before they experience their unfair and brutal deaths! stop thinking about going vegan and just do it. stop making excuses on how hard it is to go vegan because itâ€™s not! break your habits of eating shit, puss and flesh. change the way your babies and children grow up so they donâ€™t have to make the change when they are older. you teach your children to love and be gentle towards animals but then you feed them â€œhappy mealsâ€ and hot dogs! stop and think about the terror in their little faces if they actually knew what they were eating. if they saw the photos of the same animals they love being killed. i will not apologize if my posts are getting to you because that is exactly my goal. iâ€™m an animal activist. i have chosen to be their voice!

text:
dec 6. day of remembrance. 
i have been extremely open about how i did not get justice when i was raped at 18. i turned that into @projectfword. i've been working with sex offenders now for years. it became my way of creating purpose out of trauma.

but on sept 12 2017, i was at a pub and was sexually assaulted again. again. in public. brazen. by a stranger. i was wearing nothing cute - it wasnt late and i wasnt drunk. again. (all of the reasons people say we are assaulted)
earlier this month, i posted that i went to court and faced the man who assaulted me. everyone said they were happy i finally found justice from the original assault --- i didnt. it was another case. 
i stayed quiet about what i was going through because many people close to me were watching all of the public #metoo cases and making horrific judgements on all ends. for the first time in my life, i felt ashamed of being a victim. 
how could this happen to me again?

i guess there is a bright side which is that i did receive "justice" in the sense that i was believed. and this is only because the brazen assault was on surveillance camera. clear.
but the entire court process was hell. i know why women dont speak up.

however - i've been doing work along the way with counselors and social workers from women's college hospital who have 10+ years experience. my case was the first case they worked where there was a 'guilty' outcome. please take that in. 
this last year almost broke me. why do i want to live in this world when this is the reality?
only 5% of sexual assaults are reported and less than half move forward. less than half of that is found in a guilty verdict. 
around 1% of all sexual assault cases ever receive court "justice". we are your friends, family, girlfriends, wives, sisters - please believe us. ..i wish i didnt have to believe it. 
my case goes to sentencing next week. authority gets to decide his punishment for my life being impacted. probably probation for me now being scared of public places. 
dec 6 is about acknowledging that we have a long way to go. i'll be spending the day recognizing the honoring the women in my life and i hope you do the same. ğŸŒ¹

text:
you have polluted my ecosystem
my air is contaminated
my rivers are blocked
my forests are ablaze 
but while i know your ruining of me was a cruel act
it was also a gift
now i have learned to care for my soil 
treat it with tenderness and care
and one day,
i will plant the seeds of strong oak trees
so the next time someone comes to tear me down 
or uproot my life
i will have no paths for destruction like you to wander down
(my original art & poem)
#recovery #mentalhealth #wellness #art #artjournal #poetry #poemsofinstagram #collage #mentalhealthawareness #metoo #poem #zines

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still, today, right now.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
last night in li a guy tried to run me down in his suv. he waited until i was in the crosswalk and then gunned for me. he was stopped at a stop sign. it was not an accident. i had to run out of the road, maybe missing the car by ten inches. when i turned around, he had braked hard in the intersection and turned around to grin at me. it was too dark to see his face. all i could catch was the glint of his teeth in the glare of a neighbourâ€™s porch light, and a silhouette. in that moment, i had no idea if he was going to get out of the car and come after me. i didnâ€™t know if he was armed. all i knew was that i was carrying two bags, and it was late, and it was dark, and the street was deserted. it was just me, and this silver suv, and a man who had just tried to kill me. (generously, shatter my ilium?)
.
i think the worst part about this is that this is so far from the worst thing thatâ€™s happened to me. i called the local police precinct, and they sent a car to meet me. i was still high on adrenaline when i gave them a statement. the white dude cop tried to calm me down, but of course i didnâ€™t really feel safe with him either. i met him in the driveway because i didnâ€™t want him in the house with my brother. he kept asking for a plate, which i didnâ€™t have. the guy had sped off towards ocean ave. it was dark. does safe exist for qtpoc? for woc? for poc/pgm? what is â€œsafeâ€? have any of us ever truly felt â€œsafeâ€?
.
there is no happy ending or moral to this story. what i have to say is this: when women and femmes and nbs talk about being terrified of men, there is really no way for cis dudes to ever get what thatâ€™s like. what if he had a gun? i donâ€™t fuckinâ€™ know, man. this is our lives. all the time. iâ€™m so tired of being tired of it all the time. i was two fuckinâ€™ blocks from my maâ€™s place. if i canâ€™t feel safe on my own street, i dunno where i can go. i donâ€™t know. i donâ€™t know, and so i keep trudging through the mire of shit. thatâ€™s what it feels like, on bad days. keep moving, because thereâ€™s nothing else we can do.
.

.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
the mirror never lies adalah film fiksi arahan kamila andini pada tahun 2011. tahun ini datang kesempatan untuk kita menontonnya bersama sama!

hari: sabtu, 8 desember 2018
jam: registrasi dibuka mulai pukul 16.00 wita 
venue: lantai 2 warung @menbrayut
.
"clothes aren't going to change the world. the women who wear them will."
.
ada keterkaitan antara ruang hidupmu (lingkungan) dengan kehidupan juga penghidupan. fashion, baik baju maupun perhiasan adalah industri penghasil limbah yang besar bagi lingkungan. myra juliarti (desainer @akusiji) dan dian suri (desainer @kunangjewelry) memiliki kesamaan semangat dalam mengawali bisnisnya agar bertanggung jawab bagi lingkungan dan sosial.

ada cerita apa saja dari mereka? bagaimana tantangan yang ada dan apakah ada harapan terwujudnya revolusi fashion di masa kini?

dengarkan semuanya di #hearmetoo session setelah pemutaran. yuk berakhir pekan bersama enam belas film festival bali!

festival ini gratis dengan komitmen zerowaste, jadi bawa tumbler/botol minumnya ya!

text:
please join wgsssa on monday, dec 10th at 7:30 p.m. in the university theater (ut-108) for a free screening of the sundance documentary half the picture followed by a q&a with filmmaker amy adrion. 
half the picture celebrates the groundbreaking work of female film directors and investigates the systemic discrimination that has denied opportunities to many talented women in hollywood.  interviews with famous directors such as ava duvernay, jill soloway, lena dunham, catherine hardwicke and miranda july are complemented by expert analysis from the acluâ€™s melissa goodman, the sundance instituteâ€™s caroline libresco, vanity fairâ€™s rebecca keegan, uscâ€™s dr. stacy smith and san diego state universityâ€™s dr. martha lauzen.  an incredibly timely film in the #metoo and time's up era, half the picture is an inspiring account of the endurance of female talent in the face of hollywood bias.

text:
a fear of sharks is considered rational, when 1 in 262,365 will experience a shark attack.

1 in 6 women will experience rape or attempted rape, and being cautious of men is seen as misandry. 
further still, for every 1000 rapes, 994 will go unpunished.

all of a sudden the fear of dipping your toes in the water just got a whole lot closer to home. 
the #metoo movement brought to our attention how frequent, and just how many people we each know, to have been affected by rape, sexual abuse and unwanted advances. one is 43,728% more likely to be raped than to be attacked by a shark. ğŸ¦ˆ

text:
hundreds of thousands of #metoo tweets are proof that sexual harassment at the workplace is alive and thriving. yet, in most of these cases, sexual harassers are let go with just a warning or worse, are treated as victims themselves.
.
it is an established fact that workplace sexual harassment is often more about the display of power and dominance over others than it is about sex. that means many sexual harassers could also be key employees at their organisations. so, it comes as a little surprise when many organisations prefer to protect these perpetrators because of business value instead of bringing them to task for their crime.
.
itâ€™s time to stop this now. remember: supporting a criminal is nearly as bad as committing the crime itself. enough is enough. letâ€™s stand in solidarity with the victims of sexual harassment from today. .
.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

text:
join us for a festive late opening tonight, 18.00-20.00 @ morley gallery.

womenâ€™s work highlights historic, modern and contemporary work by women in the southwarkâ€™s art collection.
2018 has been an important year for raising issues about womenâ€™s equality and recognition. there are many powerful stories, from the centenary of womenâ€™s partial suffrage in 1918 to the #metoo movement. this exhibition makes visible a selection of female artists and raises questions about the structures that impact the ways in which women artists are represented, displayed and collected.

featured artists include margaret sarah carpenter, prunella clough, anya gallaccio, grace golden, barbara hepworth, sarah lucas, saskia olde wolbers and bertha newcombe.

text:
are you beautiful? 
beauty is everywhere, in us and around us everyday you just have to see it with your heart and your minds eye.

there were many years when i question this for myself, are you beautiful not just my external outer shell but my internal inner shell.

then i discovered the true essesence of self love and understanding that i have to love myself truly before i can see the beauty that i hold as a person, which has been a journey. 
i no longer care about what people think of me and how they judge me because i know i come from a place of love and have so much to give to the universe and the people that i connect with are the ones that are meant to be in my life so i can give to them and them to me.

so when i look at the phase you are beautiful, i truly believe i am and all of you are as beauty is what our essence is made of. 
don't allow others to say any different and effect your way of thinking as you were put in the universe to share your essence and write your own story.

yes you are beautiful

text: reflection (movements): in the last decade several ads and social movements have sprung up to bring awareness to sexual assault including #thatsharassment, #metoo, the truth has a voice, and timeâ€™s up (zost, 2018). these operations not only aid in the promotion of sexual assault education and dispelling stigma, but they also help to encourage survivors who have yet to seek help know that they are not alone. this is the heart of the #metoo movement, which aims to give survivors a voice. this mirror reflects the twinship that survivors find in these movements with people who have gone through similar experiences as them. the mirror shows rays of light, crossing paths and shining across each other. these are the hopeful connections that take place when two or more survivors have the opportunity to meet and find solace in the sharing of one anotherâ€™s stories. local events that take place at texas a&m university san antonio include a block party to help students foster community and provide a safer alternative to partying, programming such as active bystander intervention training, national night out to bring awareness to who is in the community to support individuals, and a peaceful protest on campus against kavanaugh that took place this semester (k. frank, personal communication, october 4, 2018; r. lutz-guevara, personal communication, october 5, 2018).

we came to the general consensus that minors should not be held accountable for their communication of language and idea(l)s no matter how â€œproblematicâ€ or at odds with our own beliefs. instead as educators, we should serve to expose and equip students with critical thought, analysis, and healthy doses of opposition so that students may organically arrive at their own conclusions in a way that fits with their personal beliefs, identities, and experiences. we suggested that a good way to approach this may be to ask the student to write a text explaining, arguing, and justifying their belief as an assessment to show that they posses these skills even if they do not agree with the content or ideas we perpetuate through exploring a topic.

bengaluru, dec 6: netra pallavi m, a bharatiya janata party councilor of bruhat bengaluru mahanagara palike (bbmp) has levelled allegations of sexual harassment against her own partyâ€™s leadership.

33-year-old pallavi, who represents atturu ward in bbmp on wednesday told media persons that a few senior bjp leaders sought â€˜favoursâ€™ from certain woman councillors.

the bjp leadership, however, denied her allegations and warned her of disciplinary action if he continues to level allegation against her own party.

pallavi was unavailable for comment after her statements were aired, and her phone remained switched off.

text:
this time of year makes me anxious and overall, easily triggered. although i'm proud of my physical weight loss journey, this is also an improvement on my mental health as well. this dress in particular honestly holds triggers in a way. 
the last time i wore this outfit, i was walking out of the hospital new year's day, puzzled and scared. i couldn't think straight. any form of trust i had towards those around me was shut down. being sexually assaulted by a "friend" next to my friend was never my intentions that night. the whole situation truly dulled my personal confidence and really made me not want to live. another scar on my body of dark secrets..but refuse to keep secrets like this anymore.

it has not been an easy 2ish years but something tells me my journey isn't over with those in my life and this new chapter with my new shield of armor. â¤ï¸ each year i'm growing, even if i fall in between. .
.
.
#weightlossjourney #mentalhealth #improvement #respectwomen #nomeansno #strongwilled #womanempowerment #metoo #staystrong

text:
last night i launched shenetworks in london at wework, soho. it was my dream to take shenetworks to a bigger platform, to give my local community opportunities across the uk to collaborate and make things happen.

last night was proof to me that networking and collaboration is key to our success. the greatest gift we can give each other, is each other. the strength in the room tonight was exactly why we came into london. to be with women who want to make a difference to all of our lives, women who know the importance of working alongside each other.

our speakers jay diamond, shola kaye and susan kabani were beautifully focused on empowering women. i was proud to share the stage with them all.

the most talented and amazing anna caterina-florio hosted tonightâ€™s first event. sheâ€™s a real force of everything that shenetworks stands for and was a delight to us all the entire evening, thank you anna. itâ€™s always a pleasure to see you ğŸ’– 
thank you also must go to the shenetworks london partner ugenie for bringing such strength of community to our lives. such an honour to work alongside you.

i want to give back, support others, give you your voice back and discover new opportunities.

someone wrote in my secret santa christmas card today â€œnothing can dim your lightâ€. itâ€™s true, nothing can.

"when youâ€™ve been through some of the things that iâ€™ve been through and you try to voice your opinions, people donâ€™t get it. people donâ€™t understand why you believe the things you do. people believe what theyâ€™ve believed their whole lives and they donâ€™t want to believe anything else. my mom had to take me to planned parenthood to make sure i didnâ€™t have any form of stds or anything like that. i had to keep going to the doctors every week to keep getting tested for pregnancy just in case. there was absolutely no birth control used. there were a few times that he made me take plan b. but not every time. so when people talk about wanting to ban abortion and people are like, â€œdonâ€™t have sex,â€ thatâ€™s not it. girls arenâ€™t just going off and not being safe. there are times when things happen like that. but girls like me that have been through all of this stuff and they need that there. it really bothers me. when you try to voice that opinion people donâ€™t listen to you. especially when youâ€™re a tiny little white girl. people think i donâ€™t know what iâ€™m talking about. they think iâ€™m trying to fit in with the media and fit in with everyone else by believing a certain way. but people donâ€™t think about what people have been through that makes them believe a certain way. and itâ€™s on both sides. but after everything that iâ€™ve been through itâ€™s hard to try to make people believe things. even when people talk about, â€œoh she was probably raped for the way that she dresses.â€ but people donâ€™t think about children. i was very little. i was a little emo kid with bands shirts, jeans, and converse. that was me growing up. there was nothing to provoke that, i was just being a kid. people donâ€™t get that sometimes." -aly

text:
"it was so much for everyone. no one knew what to do. that was it. after fighting it for a year and everything we went through, it just wasnâ€™t heard. people just didnâ€™t listen. none of us knew what to do. we had to sit there and be like, â€œthat was that. we have to move on.â€ thereâ€™s no point in fighting it. we were shown that no one was on our side. we arenâ€™t going to keep trying to fight for people to be on our side. i think thatâ€™s why people are so scared to come out with it. theyâ€™re going to try to fight it and no one is going to be on their side. and then theyâ€™ll just feel worse than they already do about everything. and it just scares people. it was horrible to hear from a judge. especially from a woman. especially from a woman with kids. to listen to a mother and daughter explain all of the things that they went through and just not believe them. it was horrible to see. even my mom brought up things to me that she went through that i had no idea about that happened between them. it was horrible to hear that she wasnâ€™t believed. we put everything we had, even my money for college, in this case. and everything just all at once was over. after an entire year. heâ€™s allowed to find another job. heâ€™s allowed to do whatever. but i wonâ€™t ever get my childhood back. iâ€™m not going to get back the life that i missed out on." -aly -----

text:
"when i was about three or four my mom met my stepdad. after a month they got married. he took me in. from the ages of four to about 16 or 17 he sexually abused me. for 12 years. my mother didnâ€™t know. my grandparents didnâ€™t know. it was just me keeping it to myself for 12 years. they got divorced when i was in seventh grade. i would switch back and forth between their houses. when it was just him and me i wouldnâ€™t sleep. i had really bad insomnia. i would get about two hours of sleep a week. school was very difficult. when i got off the bus when he would pick me up from my stop i wouldnâ€™t talk to anyone. i would just rush to the car so he wouldnâ€™t ask questions or anything. when i would take a shower i would turn my phone on silent in case anyone texted me. i would turn my phone on airplane mode at night so no one would text me throughout the night. if i would get random wrong number calls it would just be accusations for hours on end. hours and hours. sometimes until like four in the morning. i would try to go to bed and then have to wake up at 5 to go to school. it was extremely rough as a child. i wasnâ€™t allowed to have friends. my gay best friend was the only guy i was ever allowed to be friends with. if i was even in a school project with a boy i would get yelled at. if i wasnâ€™t allowed to pick my group and there was a boy in my group i would have to give my stepdad proof or have my teacher send him something to show that i had to do it for school and it was mandatory." -aly
-----

enam belas film festival bali kembali hadir dalam mendukung gerakan anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan dan kelompok rentan, kali ini kami akan memutarkan beberapa karya film pendek dalam program untold.

hari, tanggal: kamis, 6 desember 2018
jam: 16.00 wita
lokasi: warung men brayut @menbrayut

diikuti oleh #hearmetoo session mengenai kekerasan berbasis gender dari sisi psikologis bersama i putu galang dharma putra yang merupakan seorang psikolog yang kini aktif di bali soul society.

festival ini gratis dengan komitmen zerowaste, jadi bawa tumbler/botol minumnya ya!

#hearmetoo #metoo #gerakbersama #hapuskekerasanseksual #enambelasffest #enambelasffestbali #saveibunuril #zerowasteevent #zerowastebali

text:
is the workplace more stressful than it was? do employees feel more under pressure than before? are staff feeling burdened by work emails around the clock? recent data and surveys suggest there is an increasing problem writes hugh pym.

now one business owner wants other employers to follow his lead and allow employees to do a four-day week and to switch off completely on the fifth day.

ankur shah runs lifestyle brands company mahabis and says he lets staff, within reason, choose where they work on the four days as long as they are in contact via email or skype.

there is also no monitoring of working hours. #youwillbearwitness #emdr #erinfado #therapydog #metoo #ptsd #peterfox #ptsdsurvivor #ptsdrecovery #ptsdawareness #stopracism #stopbullying #stopchildabuse #dissociativeidentitydisorder #cardinalpell

5 things to know about maya angelouâ€™s complicated, meaningful life

itâ€™s only fitting that the first week of u.s. national poetry month in april coincides with what would have been the 90th birthday of the poet maya angelou, who died may 28, 2014, at the age of 86.
 but while sheâ€™s best known today for her writing â€” as the author of more than 30 books and the recipient of more than 50 honorary degrees â€” she had many different careers before becoming a writer, and all before the age of 40, as time pointed out in her  2014 obituary . such jobs included: cook, waitress, sex-worker, dancer, actor, playwright, editor at an english-language newspaper in egypt, calypso singer ,  and cast member of the opera  porgy and bess.  in fact, h er name is more of a stage name than a pen name; she was born marguerite annie johnson in st. louis in 1928, but in the 1950s came up with â€œmaya angelou,â€ which is a  portmanteau  of sorts, by combining her childhood nickname and a riff on her then-husbandâ€™s surname.  in a  google  doodle marking her april 4 birthday, she can be heard reading â€œ  still  i rise , â€ alongside testimonials from her son  guy johnson, oprah winfrey, laverne cox, alicia keys, america ferrera, and martina mcbride. the 15-time grammy-winner keys calls her a â€œrenaissance woman,â€ while 14-time grammy nominee mcbride says angelou inspired her to write her own songs. winfrey, who has called angelou  a mentor , says that â€œmaya angelou is not what she has  done or written or spoken, itâ€™s how she did it all. she moved through the world with unshakeable calm, confidence, and a fiery, fierce grace and abounding love.â€ here are five things to know about the literary legend:  i know why the caged bird sings  was her first book
 as the world marks her birthday in 2018, maya angelouâ€™s breakout work is particularly relevant to the national conversation. long before the #metoo and #timesup movements brought sexual assault into the national conversation, she wrote in her 1969 memoir about her own experience with sexual trauma, and how her motherâ€™s boyfriend raped her when she was a child. he was convicted and imprisoned, and after his release he was be

text:
menurut catatan tahunan komnas perempuan di tahun 2017, dari 350.000 kasus kekerasan terhadap perempuan yang tercatat, 20% diantaranya terjadi di ruang publik. sementara sisanya yang terbesar adalah dalam hubungan pribadi dan keluarga. bahkan dalam dunia maya dan teknologi komunikasi, kekerasan seksual terjadi.
korban masih saja disalahkan, aparat hukum pun melakukan viktimisasi sementara pelaku bebas berkeliaran. belum adanya aturan khusus tentang kekerasan seksual membuat pencegahan dan penanganan kekerasan seksual terhambat.
namun begitu sudah ada ruu penghapusan kekerasan seksual yang direncanakan menjadi payung hukum masih belum disahkan hingga kini.
yuk kita kumpul bersama untuk mendorong pengesahan ruupks.
@kopri_official

baby gates! 
babies! and dogs!  have a safe place for the dog to be where it doesn't need to worry about being disturbed. gate off the kitchen or laundry room, or master bedroom. dog can count on baby-free floor space and uninterrupted sleep. parents can count on no bites to the face or muzzle punches. crawling babies and toddlers are at risk for a while, and fearful dogs need protection from crossing the line. i much prefer careful management rather than relying on training when the risks are gigantic. we love having an extended gate that opens with one hand and allows us to have the dogs in part of the kitchen, near the action, but separated from toddler unless directly closely supervised.

look out! itâ€™s the leftâ€™s fun police!  in the #metoo era, any remote suggestion of men â€œtaking advantageâ€ of innocent young women must be wiped away from history. â€œbaby, its cold outside,â€ a classic christmas song for over 50 years, must be banned from the airwaves! it doesnâ€™t matter that 94% of the radio stations listeners said no to the ban, the radio station caved to the 6% that voted the christmas song is inappropriate. outraged feminists that make up 6% can dictate to the majority what they can and cannot listen to at christmas?

it is a cold and lonely christmas when the #metooers are huddled near the space heater with their six cats, drinking wine and eating that pizza for one as the resentment against men festers inside them. if they canâ€™t have fun, then no one deserves to have fun.

stop in the name of the fun police! rudolph you are â€œproblematicâ€, the fun police pronounced about â€œrudolph, the red-nosed reindeerâ€ the favorite christmas show of millions of children around the world. seems rudolphâ€™s dad was bullying him and donner was a racist bigot against â€œred-nosedâ€ reindeer. presumably this fell in the same category as atrocities committed against native americans. who knew?

no justice! no charlie brown thanksgiving! charlie brown and the whole gang (including that bigot snoopy) were accused of bigotry and racism against the only black child in the â€œhoodâ€ when he was seated across from the gang. the fun police claimed this was blatant racism when actually he got the best seat in the house. whereâ€™s black lives matter when you need them?

how dare you! you are not inclusive! the fun police charged the â€œvictoria secretâ€ show featuring beautiful women dressed as angels in skimpy outfits. where are the trans gender women? where are the lesbians? where are the plus, plus size models? they need representation too!

text:
really struggling today and tonight as iâ€™ve been thinking about a polygamy criminal case that will be in the courts tomorrow.... i have soo many thoughts and i cannot even put them together!!! a woman was beat by her husband, she fled the aub polygamous group with her children, husband bails himself out, threatens her on a recorded phone call to drop charges, case takes 2 years to go to trial, utahâ€™s previous attorney general mark shurtleff (who was charged with accepting bribes and such) is the attorney for the polygamist husband, and now the state of utah is planning to plea down the charges without even taking the case to trial ..... did i miss something or does so much make sense now?

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

"it was september of last year when i was in an almost-empty bus, heading home. i chose to sit in the farthest sear. not too long after i got in, a group of five men got in and scattered themselves across the bus. the youngest of them, who seemed to be around my age, sat across from the long rear seat of the bus next to me. the other four had the audacity to turn all the way around to face me and stare shamelessly with smug looks on their faces. no words were said - just the incessant stare directed at me by all five of them was enough to make me feel defenseless, nervous and angry. i've never had the courage to speak up, but i stared directly at the boy next to me. i wondered what would happen if i stared back. he had no dignity to look away. in fact, staring back seemed to excite them even more. i went on to ask him, "à¶‡à¶ºà·’ à¶”à·„à·œà¶¸ à¶¶à¶½à¶±à·Š à¶‰à¶±à·Šà¶±à·™? à¶šà·™à¶½à·Šà¶½à·™à¶šà·Š à¶¯à·à¶šà¶½à· à¶±à·à¶¯à·Šà¶¯ à¶¸à·“à¶§ à¶šà¶½à·’à¶±à·Š? text:
@maddowshow @nyt.fi @huffpost i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still, today, right now.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

a non

text:
so got in a fight with a group of friends  about sexual assault jokes  obviously i don't find them funny. the one guy made a point to say "it's just a joke" to which i ended up replying "it's not a joke to victims who wake up in the middle of night panting from the nightmares of an abuser. to victims who can't even do their normal every day activities because it reminds them of their abuser." and we are no longer friends anymore.

text:
look out! it's the #funpolice coming to ruin christmas songs & children's shows near you! 
look out! itâ€™s the leftâ€™s fun police! 
in the #metoo era, any remote suggestion of men â€œtaking advantageâ€ of innocent young women must be wiped away from history. â€œbaby, its cold outside,â€ a classic christmas song for over 50 years, must be banned from the airwaves! it doesnâ€™t matter that 94% of the radio stations listeners said no to the ban, the radio station caved to the 6% that voted the christmas song is inappropriate. outraged feminists that make up 6% can dictate to the majority what they can and cannot listen to at christmas?

it is a cold and lonely christmas when the #metooers are huddled near the space heater with their six cats, drinking wine and eating that pizza for one as the resentment against men festers inside them. if they canâ€™t have fun, then no one deserves to have fun.

stop in the name of the fun police! rudolph you are â€œproblematicâ€, the fun police pronounced about â€œrudolph, the red-nosed reindeerâ€ the favorite christmas show of millions of children around the world. seems rudolphâ€™s dad was bullying him and donner was a racist bigot against â€œred-nosedâ€ reindeer. presumably this fell in the same category as atrocities committed against native americans. who knew?

no justice! no charlie brown thanksgiving! charlie brown and the whole gang (including that bigot snoopy) were accused of bigotry and racism against the only black child in the â€œhoodâ€ when he was seated across from the gang. the fun police claimed this was blatant racism when actually he got the best seat in the house. whereâ€™s black lives matter when you need them?

how dare you! you are not inclusive! the fun police charged the â€œvictoria secretâ€ show featuring beautiful women dressed as angels in skimpy outfits. where are the trans gender women? where are the lesbians? where are the plus, plus size models? they need representation too!

it comes down to this. will you continue to let a small minority of nagging scolds ruin your holidays and relationships? who made them the moral authority in this country and why do companies listen to them and cave in? because they are loud and persistent

every year, we invite survivors of domestic violence and sexual assault to visit our holiday gift store. they are able to shop for their family members and themselves. although they get to shop for their gifts, all of the gifts are free! we are only able to do this because of the care and support we receive from our communities.

if you are unable to donate, please support us by spreading the word!! suggested items to donate:
non gender specific gifts for adults: new scarves, hats, gloves, socks, bath/shaving sets. small household items: new toasters, blenders, dish sets, blankets. gifts for teens: gift cards, nail polish sets, cosmetics, head phones.

thank you community for all you do to support survivors!!! for more information about where to drop off donations, please contact:  ldegaray@elprograma.org

text:
@arimelber @donlemoncnn @seanhannity @maddowshow @thejimmydoreshow @cnn @nbcnews wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
time to stir that congress cauldron.... alexandria ocasio-cortez- born october 13, 1989, in #newyorkcity, ocasio-cortez worked as lead educational strategist at gageis, inc. and was an educator at the nonprofit national hispanic institute. she is the member-elect of the u.s. house of representatives for new york's 14th congressional district and will be the youngest woman to serve in congress in #unitedstates history.

ayanna s. pressley- born february 3, 1974 in #chicago, illinois, pressley was the first black woman elected to the boston city council where she currently serves as an at-large member and is the first black woman elected to congress from #massachusetts as member-elect of the u.s. house of representatives, serving massachusetts's 7th congressional district.

ilhan omar- born october 4, 1981 in mogadishu, #somalia, omar is the director of policy & initiatives of the women organizing women network and is the first somali american elected to legislative office in the united states where she is the member-elect of the u.s. house of representatives for #minnesota's 5th congressional district.

debra a. haaland- born december 2, 1960, in winslow, #arizona, haaland is part #nativeamerican and member of the #lagunapueblo people. she is a former chair of the democratic party of #newmexico and the member-elect of the u.s. house of representatives for new mexico's 1st congressional district.

veronica escobar- born september 15, 1969 in el paso, #texas, escobar served as a county commissioner and county judge for #elpaso county from 2010 to 2017 and is the member-elect of the u.s. house of representatives for texas's 16th congressional district.

sharice davids- born may 22, 1980 in #frankfurt, west germany, davids is native american and a member of the #hochunk nation. she is an attorney and the member-elect of the u.s. house of representatives for #kansas's 3rd congressional district.

text:
why you keep attracting toxic men, what men want and why self-love is key.
.
woke up to this message from a man i dated a while back.
.
"any man that dates you and marries you will be a better lucky man.  i hope he isnâ€™t a dummy like me that messed things up.  wish you the best mar.  you are an amazing woman. take care."
.
here is the thing about this.
.
iâ€™m going to be damn honest.
.
i felt amazing.ğŸ˜
i felt empowered.ğŸ’ªğŸ¼
i felt â€œyour lossâ€ ğŸ’ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸
it elevated my damn ego.ğŸ¤¦ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸
.
iâ€™m not going to lie.
.
then i took a moment to reflect and come back down to earth.
.
is not the person who said this to me that made me feel great this morning.
.
or knowing that he realized this way too late.
.
or knowing that is his damn loss and i wonâ€™t go back there ever ever.
.
is the knowing i always had in me when iâ€™ve dated anyone that i am enough, worthy and amazing.
.
is the knowing that i feel and believe at my core any man would be lucky to have me.
.
is the knowing that even if it doesnâ€™t work out it is a great lesson and life experience.
.
here is something i've learned from my own journey and the women i help.
.
every man you have encountered and dated always comes back one way or the other.
.
or maybe you keep attracting the same type of men (rules still apply).
.
ex's that are toxic come back because...
.
-they know you!
-they know how to manipulate you and get you mentally and emotionally.
-they know what makes you fall and take them back.
-they simply know you inside out.
-you are probably have also been fragile, naive, vulnerable, weak, easily manipulated, and doormat.
-you probably don't feel confident.
-you probably are unable to speak up for what you want.
-you probably don't know who you are because you lost yourself.
-you probably are confused on how you feel about him, gaslighting, etc.
-you are always in doubt, fear and anxiety.
-you are probably terrified and scared of being alone, so you rather be with him knowing he is not good for you, than being alone.
-you also believe â€œyou are the woman that will change himâ€ and â€œyour love will heal him.â€
.
but you know at your core you deserve better, that this isn't for you.
.

text:
classic christmas song, "baby, it's cold outside," is getting a chilly response from canadian radio stations.

according to reports, at least two of the country's biggest media giants (rogers media and bell media) have pulled the song out of rotation, in the wake of the #metoo movement.

the song written back in 1944, has been facing scrutiny over what some say are inappropriate lyrics.

some of the lyrics say the following:

i simply must go (but baby, it's cold outside)
the answer is no (but baby, it's cold outside)

the neighbors might think (baby, it's bad out there)
say what's in this drink? (no cabs to be had out there)

so really i'd better scurry (beautiful please don't hurry)
but maybe just a half a drink more (put some records on while i pour)

what are your thoughts on the lyrics/song? tell us below!

text:
the year 2008; when ghana had just one shopping mall (koala doesn't count), a time when the word cool didn't really vibe with anything. even our music videos back then were very very uncool.

there were no online trends to follow, no smartphones to make our lives more colorful (i mean all we had was cell phones with #polyphonic ringtones & mp3 players), no posting of pics to get the most likes [even with #myspace], no #dms to slide in, no social media challenges, the #metoo movement wasn't a thing, uber & taxify were unheard of, no jumia foods and waakye guy guy to order from, mobile money didn't even exist chaaaley . there wasn't even a cool concept store to get fun & amazing stuff from.

and then....

text:
culture & arts
in a crowded theater, she accused neil degrasse tyson of rape. eight years later, her story is news.
what tchiya amet began in 2010 reached a kind of fruition last week when two other women came forward with allegations of sexual misconduct.
by bill bradley

her mic cut out before she had finished accusing neil degrasse tyson of sexual assault, but tchiya amet el maat went on anyway, talking loudly enough that even people in the back of the theater got the message. â€œi donâ€™t know how i did that,â€ amet, now a natural health therapist and wellness coach, told huffpost recently. â€œi have a very soft voice.â€ it was april 21, 2010. tyson was doing a q&a segment at a nova sciencenow cosmic conversation event at san franciscoâ€™s palace of fine arts theatre. there, in front of a live audience, with â€œnovaâ€ executive producer paula apsell watching, amet confronted the famous astrophysicist. â€œiâ€™m here in honor of all the people that you raped, assaulted, harassed, violated, denied,â€ she said, â€œand for the lives that you affected and for the lives of their parents and their friends and everyone that was involved when you were a ta in grad school at ut austin in 1984 â€• including myself.â€ to our knowledge, the incident received no media attention. amet couldâ€™ve sworn the event was taped, but no broadcast exists. â€œnovaâ€ â€œdoesnâ€™t have recorded footage of that event,â€ a representative of roslan & campion pr firm said. as far as anyone not in the theater that day was concerned, the first public accusation of sexual misconduct against neil degrasse tyson simply never happened

text:
whoâ€™s to blame|i was 5 years old, surrounded by a loving family who loved god and loved people. i can still remember the dress that my mom dressed me in on that sunday morning. it was a yellow dress with frills and ruffles. my hair done in perfect braids adorned with yellow barrettes. on this particular sunday, at the beginning of the church service, i had to go to the bathroom. 
i made my way down the stairs to the bathroom, upon exiting i found myself being abruptly picked up and pushed up against the wall. confused & disoriented, i finally realized that i was being held by a young man that apparently followed me and waited for me. he proceeded to pull my dress up. i remember the lace that was sown around the trim of my dress. he placed his hand in my panties and began to touch me. i was left feeling scared & confused. he continued to molest me for some time after that day which started to seem like it was a regular part of life. during that time i kept what was happening a secret as i was afraid i would be judged. soon came more young men that began to molest me. i started to think that there was a stamp on my forehead that said: â€œtouch her.â€ i was molested until the age of 11 years old. the years that followed, i carried the guilt of that pain. i didnâ€™t love who i saw in the mirror, and i blamed myself for what happened to me. i started to have low self-esteem, i cried a lot, and i believed i wasnâ€™t good enough. now that i am an adult, whose to blame for what happened to me??? for years i blamed myself and believed i was the cause of the trauma that happened to me. but why do we do this to ourselves. why do we blame the victim. why do we then point fingers at them for not telling what happened to them until years later. why do we shame them? why do we point fingers? so i ask whose to blame, the 5 year old in this photo or....... @metoomvmt @timesupnow #survivor #notavictim of #sexualabuse #beyondthebarriers of #depression there is #hope #selflove #selfcare #melaningirlmovement #hopestillstands @essence  @redtabletalk #metoo #timesup #bmore #dc #dmv #baltimore

text:
i had to take a minute to look at myself. to see myself from the outside. to see the face of a girl who has survived numerous traumas and is still pushing forward. i wish i could feel it more, but i want to tell her i'm proud of her and that she's kind, compassionate and principled...in spite of abuse and rape, and people not always being so kind to her. i wanted to remind her that she's empathetic and brave, and that it's okay to hurt. 
#ptsd #ptsdsurvivor #cptsd #complexptsd #bipolardepression #bpd #bipolar #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #mentalillness #trauma #abuse #domesticviolence #metoo #nomeansno #survivor #brave #endthestigma #breakthestigma #selfcare #selflove

â³ the rise of internet changed the way we protest. authors divide the history of activism in three periods :
â€œactivism before cyberspace : in this period, actors are local and their engagement is physical, the flow of information is slower and restricted to traditional media, social movements are organized around leaders and the interaction with citizens is lower than todayâ€™s activism.
cyberactivism 1.0 : this time actors may be international or regional and their engagement is still offline. social movements have more horizontal organization attached either to the ngos or a leader. beside traditional media, e-mail and websites remain the main communication tools though the flow of information is still restricted and limited to organizers. unlike the previous period, the interaction between citizens is partially online and offline.
cyberactivism 2.0 : todayâ€™s activists are globally and horizontally self-organized. their engagement is online, instant and permanent. they communicate through social media and there is a constant flow information. they engage mostly online and partially also offline.â€ [23]
ğŸ“±the usual channels cyber-activists use were social media or blogs. but what we see more and more in digital activism is the use of podcasts.
ğŸ™ a podcast that illustrates this new tool is @yessspodcast. in the latest episode (05/12/18), one of the co-host said that after #metoo, we heard a lot of testimonies about what women live(d) but now, what? what can we do as â€œnormalâ€ citizens? she explained that their podcast was made to share concrete strategies women can use to try to escape harassment or help someone in trouble. the podcast is also there to try to change the social point of view as we often talk about victims and rarely about the other part of the aggression (the culprit). so the podcast aims to make people think about the why of those actions, it aims to talk about patriarchy, about toxic masculinity, etc. (personal translation) [24].

text:
equality bootcamp in lund, sweden â€“ may 2018

lÃ¦rke, sydslesvig: (ğŸ“·: @laerke.rahr)
nsus main theme in 2018 is equality, and it is deeply rooted in gender equality. 
in november 2017 the viral #metoo movement was born, and countless survivors of sexual abuse and violence have spoken up about their experiences since. the discussion about gender and the power attributed to it, is more present in the media and our daily lives than ever. 
the â€œnordic lifestyleâ€ is often praised in the media for its good healthcare and school systems. but how much equality does the north really have? 
this is where nsu has been aiming its focus towards this year - to ask the difficult questions about inequality in the nordic countries. are national and sexual minorities in the nordic countries treated with the same respect as the majority? how do we ensure integration for the people, who need it the most? how do we include those, who have less? is equality or equity the best tool? how do we practice a good example at home in our youth organisations?

the youth of the north have had the opportunity to discuss these matters together during the events of this year, and to come up with possible solutions on a local level. it is important to recognize the inequality that plays out right in front of our eyes, and to do something about it. 
#nsu#nordiskeunge#unginorden

text:
in honour of today, the national day of remembrance and action on violence against women, i want to share a story, and a resource that has been so influential for my healing journey. this isnâ€™t easy to do, but i hope that it can raise awareness and provide support for those who may need it, even if just one person can feel less alone. 
tw: sexualized violence, sexual assault â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
4 months ago, i was drugged in an environment i perceived to be safe, while out with coworkers in downtown victoria. i woke up 8 hours later in a hospital, in pain, injured, and with no memory . 
thankfully, a friend took me to the victoria sexual assault centre, where i received immediate support. they have provided me with long-term counselling for free (which they offer for immediate trauma or any previous trauma for anyone). i donâ€™t know how i would have gotten through this without their services, and without the support of my friends and family. i am eternally grateful. 
currently, every day is a new battle, and every aspect of my life is different, but the counsellors at the vsac have been there to guide me through it. it makes me sick to know that this is continuing to happen to women worldwide. 
itâ€™s time to fucking stand up, raise our voices for those who canâ€™t, and say enough is enough. believe survivors, advocate for survivors, and hold people to a higher standard. 
to anyone struggling today or any day, i am here to talk, always â¤ï¸ #metoo #believewomen

text: five things about me: 1) i was 14 the first time i got stoned 2) that same year i was raped by a 21 year old 3) at 19 i was lost in a physically abusive relationship 4) the following year i got pregnant and had an abortion (thank god for #plannedparenthood!) i had to borrow money for the procedure. i have detached myself from these memories so that i could survive the pain, confusion, and shame they bring up for me. 5) it wasnâ€™t until i met my husband that i truly began to believe a life full of joy and happiness, and satisfaction was available for me. integrating that young woman with who i am today is empowering and healing. sharing my story reminds me that life is not so different for any of us â€” we all have what it takes to overcome our required challenges. #fivethingsaboutme #decemberreflections2018 #day5 #metoo #strong #mymessybeautifullife (thank you @susannahconway for the prompt!)

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
had a really good yoga class which was really nice... and somewhat unexpected as i was in a horrible head space.
ğŸ™

shortly before lunch - and my noontime yoga - a song came on. it's a beautiful song. i love it..... loved it. today it caused such an anxiety attack that i wasn't sure if i'd survive. it was horrible!
ğŸ’§

it took me back to the summer of 2016 at "the event of the summer" that i look forward to it every year. it was this same song that played that brought up memories of my dad - who had passed away almost exactly 3 months previous. i excused myself and ran off  for privacy so i could have a cry and not have to listen to the song. ğŸ’§

after i returned to the party, i started drinking. partially to numb my feelings, and partially to have a good time.
ğŸ’§

things went bad. real bad.
ğŸ’§

by the time i realized that i drank way too much, it was too late.
ğŸ’§

i have so much shame over that whole incident. more happened, but i can't go there right now. that song didn't trigger me to the end of the evening and the assault; it triggered me to the point of the evening that i made the decision to start drinking to forget. ğŸ’§

i find it so hard to move on; to get over it and relax around the people who were there. i spoke with a couple of them after - to explain and apologize but sometimes it doesn't feel like enough. ğŸ’§

the important part is i feel better... at the moment. that insane anxiety from earlier has been replaced by shame and guilt which i deal with on a somewhat regular basis from that day.
ğŸ’§

shame is normal. we all feel shame now and then for different reasons at different intensities. it shouldn't be shut away as it won't go away unless you talk about it. ğŸ’§

that's why i decided to share.
ğŸ™

â€œshe was in the company of othersâ€
â€œshe stayed home after darkâ€
â€œshe wasnâ€™t so friendlyâ€

this focus places the responsibility of the prevention of sexual violence and rape solely on young girls and women and not on the perpetrators, where it belongs.

letâ€™s stop blaming her when we need to encourage her.

text:
today is my 19th birthday. this past year, like many before it, had many trials. there has been several times where i felt close to giving up and ending it, or that things were so hopeless that i needed a hero to save me. so this year i decided to end the hopelessness and became my own hero. i saved myself and no matter how long it takes or how hard i have to work to get there, i will rise. 
this is my birthday present to myself as well as a reminder to any of you out there who may be struggling right now that it will get better, but to do so you have to fight like hell. fight. grow. succeed. and to any of you who may share my birthday, happy birthday!!!!! #birthday #artistsoninstagram #art #watercolor #selfportriat #me #growthmindsetğŸŒ± #growthmindset #growth #journey #portrait #mentalhealth #metoo #mentalhealthawareness #colorpencil #clouds #pink #pinkclouds

@arimelber @donlemoncnn @seanhannity @maddowshow @thejimmydoreshow @cnn @nbcnews bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin

text: in the age of #metoo, this could not have been a timelier read. i happened to read this the same week as the kavanaugh hearings and was struck by how prescient @emilygiffinauthor was when she conceived this novel. in all we ever wanted, two parents navigate doing right by their child (and doing right may not always mean what one thinks it should mean) after one photograph alters everything. the depth and heart and tenderness of this book had me reading it with my hand over my open mouth, identifying with so much of what was happening and haunted by the echoes of the real-life hearings going on at the same time. absorbing and thought-provoking.  #rosiereads

text:
@arimelber @donlemoncnn @seanhannity @maddowshow @thejimmydoreshow @cnn @nbcnews bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text: â€œway back when wednesdayâ€ obviously iâ€™m late to the â€œold headshotâ€ day posts, but i was pulling out christmas crap & decorations & found this photo ğŸ“· my first headshot ever at age 18! i donâ€™t remember the photographerâ€™s name to give him credit. ( he was dating michelle pfeifferâ€™s sister at the time & i was very impressed by that ğŸ˜‚) it was the very first shot of the day & that ended up being the one my agent liked the most. i booked some commercials, a music video, a cheesy tv show, & got a line in a movie & sag eligible w/ this picture. i still have the @tiffanyandco silver heart necklace i wore in this photo. itâ€™s in black & white because color head shots werenâ€™t really around yet ... ğŸ¤” i had a pager for auditions & used to have to pull over to find pay phones to call back for details. cell phones werenâ€™t around either. ğŸ™€iâ€™m so old! ğŸ™„ anyways: what i would tell my 18 year old self is to: put myself out there, pursue your dreams & donâ€™t waste so much time on boys! i was so insecure & spent too much time in acting school when i should have been auditioning & hustling in plays & actually working! i kept reading / auditioning for leads in movies when i should have been playing cheerleader #1 just to get some on set experience! i hated working in the modeling industry because i was constantly told that i should model & then when i did, people picked me apart, told me to lose weight w/ cocaine & constantly insulted me while simultaneously hitting on me.... but acting was great & although there were always creepy â€œproducersâ€ that i just avoided... i felt that i could be more of myself & participate in creative projects without compromising my dignity. my life took me in a different direction & i had kids & never returned to pursue what i loved.... iâ€™m writing a script now. life goes by fast & itâ€™s ok to put dreams on hold for awhile. donâ€™t give up your creative pursuits just because you arenâ€™t 18 anymore... there is only one you in the world ğŸŒ w/ your voice âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨#thisis18 #longtimeago #nytgender #girlgaze #oldheadshot #metoo #beforeinstagram #backintheday #faith

text: it must be noted that women did not experience complete social liberation, although this newfound intellectual enlightenment was the first step into gaining social reform. it would be foolish to consider their intellectual liberation without consideration of female authorship; women were published at a higher rate in circulating libraries than independent publishing companies, which furthered their intellectual liberation, for they were given the opportunity to construct their own novels. women were of course met with disapproval and criticism, yet this did not heed the grandiose opportunities women were met with as a result of the circulating libraries.

text:
when women come together, magic happens.. .
.
the past weekend we were in the company of africa's most inspiring and powerful women at the @motsepefoundation sdg5 breakfast. some, we are fortunate enough to have as our advisors. .
.
we were inspired by keynotes, panel discussions and the presence of thought leaders such as un deputy secretary general, amina mohammed, graca machel, thuli madonsela, and our amazing wef family,  rapelang rabana, naadiya moosajie among others.
.
.
thank you dr precious motsepe and the motsepe foundation for hosting this beautiful event. we look forward to working together to accelerate progress on sdg5 by 2030 and onwards. .
.
"freedom cannot be achieved unless women have been emancipated from all forms of oppression". (nelson mandela)

text: back in february i was diagnosed with major clinical depression, ptsd, and general anxiety disorder. leading up to that diagnosis i was struggling a lot just to get through a day and was very close to being involuntarily admitted for 72 hours by the time my mom dragged me to get help. however, one day during what i  call my â€˜spiralâ€™ i had a good day which is when i took this picture and have held onto it for over a year now. i donâ€™t know how i did it, but i took a picture that made me feel powerful, sexy, womanly, independent, and strong at a time where i felt like anything but that. even though there is a 20 to 30 pound difference between this picture and where i am now i thought it was the perfect picture to end the small collection of before pictures i have been sharing over the past few days.

text: my best friend/a brother. um it is the day before tomorrow in a future sense of the past. this post talk will get weird. starting to feel like that's not home anymore, it'll always be home in some ways, although so much has changed i will not live there. about cities and towns and moving while adult...kinda adult. lived in the twin cities a bit, and it's weird the versus of alternating currents via minneapolis/st paul. 2 years and a month or so in, recognising this could be a home town to be from temporary or permanent depending on life. very large cities around here. happy to live on the block i am. alternating currents between those cities as well. from origins to mentalities to pronunciation, ect. i like where i work. i like where i am sometimes. it's a home cooking family jam. to know that these are people with established lives here. as we enter each others lives it gets confusing. i've never worked for you before, yet you are as if in an alternate universe 1000 miles from, foster mom, best friend, the veterinarian, and they've all just been living out here. diversity is very important for many reasons including ptsd and welcoming new ways of life, along with all the awesomeness. we live in a house made of each other. #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors #home #timeandspace #alternatingcurrents #alternateuniverse #donthitpeopleintheheadandtakeawayhealthcare #survivingdoesntmeanhealthyliving

text:
i saw an old friend yesterday that i am no longer friends with out and about downtown. they never saw me. i was driving in my car, they were walking on the sidewalk and we were both going in the same direction. honestly, it was kind of mind boggling to come face to face with their existence because i forgot for a while they even existed. â¡ï¸you know when that happens?â¬…ï¸
i say old friend because weâ€™re not friends anymore. this person exploited me under the guise of being an â€œartistâ€ and totally violated my trust. my body. our friendship.
.
when i saw them out and about, all these feelings rose to the surface and bombarded me with images, feelings, and events that i stuffed down at the time. i started shaking and wanted to cry. i went home and kept asking myself, why did the universe want me to see them? why now? and how interesting this person never saw me, i never entered into their reality. we almost collided and crossed paths, but at the last second it changed, they went down another street. the universe just wanted me to see them, not interact. why did all of this happen?
âœ”ï¸for me to realize i still have feelings about what happened. âœ”ï¸to acknowledge i have challenges trusting people and i havenâ€™t healed this yet.
âœ”ï¸for me to have a true â€œbirds-eyeâ€ perspective about the situation with me on the outside seeing them from afar...and to see i truly am better off without their presence in my life.
âœ”ï¸to remind me: this person and the part they played in my life is still affecting me and i need to do some shedding/releasing so i can heal. truly heal.
â¡ï¸if i hadnâ€™t seen them, would i know the information i have now, after seeing them/ processing/giving myself space? itâ€™s only when things get real â€œfront and centerâ€ for me, when iâ€™m faced head-on with the healing that is left to do, that i can empower myself to make a change. you have to be aware, conscious of it or it becomes buried to get rediscovered later..
.
i want to trust and love again with an open heart. as iâ€™m sure you can probably tell, this wasnâ€™t the first time someone violated me and my trust, but this one was the one that catalyzed me into developing and creating my business. (continued in comments)â¤µï¸

text:
domestic bliss - 2018
digital 
a womanâ€™s world - week 5
social media has been set alight this week with the #hearmetoo movement. the annual campaign against gender-based violence that runs for 16 days from november 25th until 10th december.

for over a week now, i have been reading and watching social media as it fires up the voices of so many women across the globe. un women produced an interesting article called '16 ways, 16 days: your guide to ending violence against women'. as i read through the article, it said one way to help was to get creative, which of course, was an absolute must for me! so, with orange, the colour of the movement in mind, i made a piece of work called domestic bliss. it is part of my year long project called a woman's world, where i will explore news stories and world issues faced by women in 2018-2019.

text:
some people have come back to me and ask â€œwhy do i still have these feelings?â€ well, my dear, you are going to always feel them until you no longer do. but now that you see it from a different perspective, you respond to it differently and it doesnt control you or cause you to make toxic choices...
healing doesnt mean the trauma or the feelings disappear, it means you able to accept that part of yourself and love it regardless!

text:
i trade my art for life, most probably because of #yayoikusama 
by chance i bought her #bibliography (ages ago i had a habit to wander around book shops/libraries, just for the sake of finding/meeting the right book), i was completely absorbed in her words, or her world... her determination, her obsession and her madness were insanely attractive/admiring/inspiring; she says "art keeps her alive" #metoo 
to feel how she feels, i sat myself on the gallery floor, drew like her, tried to get the mindset of her #obsessive impulse. it was somewhat meditative. #dotdotdot #victoriamiro #victoriamirogallery #popart #contemporaryart #kusama #infinty #themovingmomentwheniwenttotheuniverse #mirrorroom #bright #popcolour #doodle #draw #onthespot #urbansketch #usk #installation #art 
p.s mirror room, i was monitored by human cctv--- feeling so anxious -i couldn't enjoy at all; 
p.p.s the guy who timed me with a stopwatch; i'd appreciate if he could tell me how much time i could spend inside... alone... beforehand 
p.p.p.s porridge of today features lots of seeds #banana and #driedpineapple @urbanfruituk
p.ppps day5 #christmastree is hidden in my #sketches #visualdiary #minimalism #instakusama #kusamaart

text:
if i was to ask you to stand in front of your mirror and tell me what you see, whatâ€™s the first thought that comes to your mind? .
.
is the first thought one of love, or instant criticism? .
.
what if i asked you to post a picture on social media of yourself makeup free, looking just how you do after you wake up?  whatâ€™s the first thought that comes to mind?  hell no! right?  have you ever stopped to ask yourself why judgment is the first thing we default to about ourselves?
.
.
when we are born into this world, we are so open to the truth of life. all we see is good, and all we know is that if thereâ€™s something we donâ€™t like, we speak up with our screaming voice. if thereâ€™s something we love, we turn to it over and over. our eyes are open to adventure and wonder!
.
.
somewhere along the way we become exposed to opinions of others, rules of our parents, and expectations of society. suddenly our eyes of wonder become eyes of criticism and judgment.  the one we judge the most is ourself. we arenâ€™t good enough, fast enough, skinny enough, too many rolls, pimples, and gray hairs. .
.
if we are really unhappy with parts of ourselves - because we were once taught to be - we engage in self harming behavior such as abuse of food, alcohol, sex or cigarettes. the cycle you have been in for most of your life is due to internal criticism, judgment, and lack of acceptance.
.
.

text: â€œhow do you handle receiving prejudice from your own community? thatâ€™s the complexity of colorism: itâ€™s a preference for lighter skin within people of the same racial group. growing up, the only black female celebrities i saw were light-skinned. think beyoncÃ©, rihanna, mariah carey, nicki minaj, tyra banks, halle berry...etc. there was a period in my life where the darkness of my skin made me feel...ugly. i was often told, â€œyouâ€™re pretty for a black girlâ€ or â€œyouâ€™d be even prettier if you were lighter.â€ a lot of these comments came from black boys, and later men. i had to undergo a mental transformation where i accepted and embraced my features, including my afro textured hairâ€”which i never saw represented. thatâ€™s why movies like black panther, and actresses such as lupita nyongâ€™o are so exciting for women who look like me. and things are slowly changing. but whenever i hear rappers talk about wanting a â€œyellow bone chickâ€, see that a makeup brand doesnâ€™t have my shade, or read interview dress tips that say â€œkeep hair professional, tidy, combed, and preferably straightâ€, i wonder if weâ€™ve come that far at all. however, i have hope that the future will be brighter for those blessed with dark skin.â€ -stella, from missouri

yesterday 20.000 people went on the street to fight for an end of violence against women. 
even though austria is the sad leader of femicides in the eu - 32 women killed in 2018 - the demonstrations were not taking place in austria - but israel. 
israel, which has more or less the same number of inhabitants like austria, counts - sadly enough - 27 women killed in 2018. 
these killings mostly take place in a domestic environment. most of the women are killed by their partner or ex-partner.
the thing that strikes me is that i had no idea about the situation in austria. even when the austrian broadcasting agency reported of the demonstrations in tel aviv, they didnâ€˜t connect it to what is going on in austria. i donâ€™t get it.

text:
"in 2015, out of 68,833,476 registered voters, 45,888,984 were women and yet nigerian women have the lowest representation in political leadership" - inec

_
african women in leadership organisation in partnership with yali lagos organizes the #womendecide awareness walk to pass across the message of women's crucial role in electoral decisionmaking.

this is a sensitization walk on women's political participation as voters and leaders and a face-to-face interaction with community leaders and stakeholders to spark decision making interest amongst women and girls.

we'll walk through ikeja city mall to johnson jakande tinubu park, alausa where would have  a 1 hour information session
date: 15th december 2018
meet up time at ikeja city mall: 7am
come ready in your black or orange tees and blue or black jeans. this will be brief and smooth.

sign up at awlo.org/womendecide to be part of this empowering walk!!

my heart got torn to pieces last night after hearing the comments justifying a vote to keep drew nelson as our cityâ€™s leader.  with a chamber audience packed, many were left shaken, in tears and had to get up and leave due to the triggering and insensitive comments made by dan shore and cheryl brown kovacic.  this year, drew nelson drunkenly fired 8 rounds in the air in a residential neighborhood in #winterpark #winterparkcolorado and asked his wife to hit him with a sledgehammer while his kids were in the house... he was arrested on domestic violence and weapons charges and ultimately entered a plea guilty on weapons charges.  he resigned from his job there.  the city of #salidacolorado ignored its constituents, ignored the voices at a community forum and voted to keep him, even after three city employees have written letters complaining about his behavior in the workplace.  the city made a horrifying statement last night about its position on leadership qualifications, city role models, #gunviolence #domesticviolence #metoo #metoomovement and basic human safety concerns.  our key vote held by a woman, took this city in a backwards direction.  i am sad today but i am not giving up.  iâ€™m calling on all people here in #salida to continue to bravely take action towards reversing this decision.  i want to thank justin critelli and mike bowers for standing up against #drewnelson i want to thank all the men and women who have spoken up, written letters, sent emails, and raised awareness of this issue.  iâ€™m now calling on #educators and #womensrights leaders #mentalhealth professionals and #guncontrol experts near and far and all local citizens to get involved.  our amazing, incredible mountain town needs you.  we can do better than this.  we donâ€™t want to be the washington redskins, or #lancemason or trump administration of local city governance. we can fix this.  we are the change.  get loud people!! #salidacolorado #winterparkcolorado #colorado #womensrightsmatter #domesticviolenceawareness #gunviolenceawareness #smashthepatriarchy #fightthepatriarchy #votewithyourdollars
